{"type":"log","step_name":"implement","message":"1. **`docker rm` without `-f` flag** (`internal/adapters/docker/runtime.go`): The `Remove` method used `docker rm` without the `-f` (force) flag, while other cleanup calls in the same file used `docker rm -f`. Without `-f`, removal fails for containers in certain states (dead, paused, etc.), and the error was silently collected but never displayed to the user.","timestamp":"2026-03-13T18:36:11.476356005Z"}
{"type":"log","step_name":"implement","timestamp":"2026-03-13T18:36:11.476360484Z"}
{"type":"log","step_name":"implement","message":"2. **Running containers were skipped** (`internal/adapters/web/handler.go`): The cleanup handlers skipped running containers entirely instead of stopping them first. If a container was still running when cleanup was triggered, it would be silently skipped and remain.","timestamp":"2026-03-13T18:36:11.476367126Z"}
{"type":"log","step_name":"implement","timestamp":"2026-03-13T18:36:11.476374991Z"}
{"type":"log","step_name":"implement","message":"3. **Ignored `UpdateRun` error**: In the \"container already gone\" path, the `UpdateRun` error was ignored while still incrementing the `deleted` count, causing the response to report success while the database flag remained unchanged.","timestamp":"2026-03-13T18:36:11.476378438Z"}
{"type":"log","step_name":"implement","timestamp":"2026-03-13T18:36:11.476382746Z"}
